From 70e391b81fe7d3f1948246a5e73b32aaa07a38f8 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Sorgelig <pour.garbage@gmail.com>
Date: Mon, 17 Jul 2017 15:38:57 +0800
Subject: [PATCH 1/1] HID: map key Europe 1 (0x32) to KEY_F24 for Keyrah

The Keyrah C64/Amiga USB keyboard adapter reports its extra
"Europe 1" scancode (HID usage 0x32) as USB HID keycode 0x32, which
hid_keyboard[] maps to Linux keycode 43 (KEY_BACKSLASH) by default --
colliding with the adapter's real backslash key. Remaps it to
KEY_F24 (194), an otherwise-unused code Main_MiSTer can bind freely.

Provenance
----------
Origin:       70e391b81fe7d3f1948246a5e73b32aaa07a38f8
              "HID: map key Europe 1(0x32) to F24 code (for Keyrah)."
              MiSTer-devel/Linux-Kernel_MiSTer, 2017-07-17, against v5.15.
              https://github.com/MiSTer-devel/Linux-Kernel_MiSTer/commit/70e391b81fe7d3f1948246a5e73b32aaa07a38f8
Author:       Sorgelig <pour.garbage@gmail.com>
Upstream:     No (verified: drivers/hid/hid-input.c's hid_keyboard[]
              table entry for USB keycode 0x32 is still 43, not 194).
              Disposition "carry" (docs/patch-provenance.md class D).
Forward-port: 5.15 -> 6.18.38, Michael C. Ferguson, 2026-07-12, task P1.9.
              Byte-identical hunk; hid_keyboard[] is unchanged since 5.15.

Signed-off-by: Sorgelig <pour.garbage@gmail.com>
Signed-off-by: Michael C. Ferguson <michael.christopher.ferguson@gmail.com>
---
diff --git a/drivers/hid/hid-input.c b/drivers/hid/hid-input.c
